      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Randolph" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Randolph" href="/user/show/1804559-randolph">Randolph</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1804559-randolph?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1804559-randolph?shelf=literature">literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1804559-randolph?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1804559-randolph?shelf=travel">travel</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1804559-randolph?shelf=biography">biography</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer567451605" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18087434768169220321">I finally finished this mother. It was given to me as a gift and I was intimidated by the heft. However, it was one of the finest books I have ever read. It is part travelog, part history, and part literature. It is one of the great books of the 20th century, a magnum opus. <br/> <br/>A detailed history of the now Balkanized Yugoslavia up to WWII. It also features some of the finest prose ever put to paper in English. In addition it gives a delightful look into West&apos;s Easter holiday in Yugoslavia in the 1</span>
  <span id="freeText18087434768169220321" style="display:none">I finally finished this mother. It was given to me as a gift and I was intimidated by the heft. However, it was one of the finest books I have ever read. It is part travelog, part history, and part literature. It is one of the great books of the 20th century, a magnum opus. <br /> <br />A detailed history of the now Balkanized Yugoslavia up to WWII. It also features some of the finest prose ever put to paper in English. In addition it gives a delightful look into West's Easter holiday in Yugoslavia in the 1930s. By turns humorous and tragic, West also imbues it with her own idiosyncratic thoughts on history, literature, and life. She obviously loves the country and its people even as she recounts the often tragic and bloody history of the Balkans that continues even today. West has one of the great voices.<br /> <br />The book features a fine essay/introduction by the unsurpassable Christopher Hitchens that is a pleasure by itself. It is the worthiest introduction to the book I can think of.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18087434768169220321" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


