  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2178991754" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2178991754" />
    <a title="Bob Newman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/72341080-bob-newman"><img alt="Bob Newman" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2178991754?book_show_action=true">Nov 09, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bob Newman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bob Newman" href="/user/show/72341080-bob-newman">Bob Newman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/72341080-bob-newman?shelf=travel">travel</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/72341080-bob-newman?shelf=yugoslav-countries">yugoslav-countries</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2178991754" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1099446039805476769">prescient grab bag of human follies<br/><br/>Whoa ! I finished reading this 1,150 page whopper of a book which took me over two months. I can&apos;t say that it was my favorite book, but it certainly impressed me. West, a British intellectual of the pre-war period, traveled to Yugoslavia for a second time with her husband. They spent only a few weeks there in the spring of 1937. BLACK LAMB AND GREY FALCON is, on the surface, a travel record of their trip around what today is Croatia, Bosnia, Serbia, Macedonia,</span>
  <span id="freeText1099446039805476769" style="display:none">prescient grab bag of human follies<br /><br />Whoa ! I finished reading this 1,150 page whopper of a book which took me over two months. I can't say that it was my favorite book, but it certainly impressed me. West, a British intellectual of the pre-war period, traveled to Yugoslavia for a second time with her husband. They spent only a few weeks there in the spring of 1937. BLACK LAMB AND GREY FALCON is, on the surface, a travel record of their trip around what today is Croatia, Bosnia, Serbia, Macedonia, Kosovo and Montenegro---i.e. most of the component parts of a country that broke up very bloodily in the 1990s. But saying that the book is a travelogue is like saying that "Hamlet" is a play. West's insights into local politics definitely presage the Yugoslavia of 55 years later, when Tito's glue finally came undone. She records the animosities between Croats and Serbs, as well as others. She devotes a lot of space to particular historical incidents, especially the assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria, the event that touched off World War I and the eventual creation of Yugoslavia (among other countries). She looks at the murders of various Serbian rulers, the pivotal battle of Kosovo in 1389 between Turks and Christian princes, traces the ups and downs of a number of Balkan rulers over time, and tells the amazing story of the Serbian army in WW I. So, we have travelogue, history, and politics. There is also philosophy and religion. She waxes eloquent about women's rights, espouses the cause of liberty and justice in the world, and loses no opportunity to attack fascism and Nazism. Though a bit softer on colonialism, she still speaks out against it. Overall, she thinks that nationalism is a positive force. Seventy-odd years and how many more massacres later? I feel it is not. Apropos of this, I didn't appreciate such references as "Slav blood", "German blood", "Slavs love to travel", "what was particularly Croat in him", "all Slavs are quarrelsome", and a host of others, but those were the times and she could not free herself entirely of such sentiments. I predict readers will feel, as I did, that a strong message of this book is that people just don't learn from history, and so are condemned to repeat it. (Not an original thought, I know, but very relevant here.)<br /><br />Her traveling companions, aside from her husband, were a Serbian Jewish intellectual who was a poet, a government official and something of a war hero, and his wife, a German, who turned out to be an out and out Nazi, the traveling companion from hell. How this marriage survived is a mystery. Probably it didn't. Her good sense of humor carried her through these difficulties. Like Freya Stark, the British traveler in Arabia, she doesn't reveal how she knew various people, why the Yugoslav government was interested in what she did or thought.<br /><br />But there is a deeper level to the book, which perhaps is why many people call this one of the great books of the 20th century. I'm not sure I agree, but as a travel book, it must be one of the best ever written. To appreciate this deeper level, you have to put yourself where West was in 1941 when the book came out. The Nazis had taken over almost all of Europe. Only Sweden, Switzerland, and the UK remained as democracies and the former two had kowtowed to Germany. London was on fire, bombs falling everywhere. The Yugoslavia she knew and loved had been bombed and invaded, taken over by murderous thugs or Nazis. In their invasion of April, 1941, the Germans bombed Belgrade with 800 planes, killing 24,000 people in a couple days. The Yugoslav government, like others in the region, could have succumbed to German demands and saved this bloodshed, but they defied the Nazis and vowed to fight. They sacrificed themselves and their people for their honor, for future history. Black Lamb and Grey Falcon refer to two kinds of sacrifice: one in local religious practice and the other in Serbian history, especially referred to in ballads commemorating the Battle of Kosovo Polje. People can be more than one thing at a time. To get the full impact of what West implied in the book, you must read it. Sometimes her prose is too wordy, her dialogues imitative of foreign speech wearying, and her digressions tiring, but there is no doubt. This is a great book. If you can stay the course, I think you will agree.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1099446039805476769" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


