<div id="review_2287866025" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2287866025" />
    <a title="Hannah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2400165-hannah"><img alt="Hannah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1512687352p2/2400165.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2287866025?book_show_action=true">Feb 07, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hannah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hannah" href="/user/show/2400165-hannah">Hannah</a>
      </span>

          marked it as to-read




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2287866025" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8505808237850343490">According to Alan Jacobs, &quot;very possibly the greatest book of the 20th century.&quot; His review is <a href='http://www.theamericanconservative.com/jacobs/on-black-lamb-and-grey-falcon/' rel='nofollow noopener'>here</a>. He also notes that the intro by Christopher Hitchens is a &quot;hit piece on the author&quot; and worth skipping. (Although I&apos;d read it anyway.)<br/><br/>I&apos;m surprised I&apos;d never heard of this book. I&apos;m particularly interested because my parents currently live in the Balkans (Albania), and my family was just weeks away from moving to Sarajevo in 1991 when the war broke out in Yugoslavia and we were relocated to Warsa</span>
  <span id="freeText8505808237850343490" style="display:none">According to Alan Jacobs, "very possibly the greatest book of the 20th century." His review is <a href="http://www.theamericanconservative.com/jacobs/on-black-lamb-and-grey-falcon/" rel="nofollow noopener">here</a>. He also notes that the intro by Christopher Hitchens is a "hit piece on the author" and worth skipping. (Although I'd read it anyway.)<br /><br />I'm surprised I'd never heard of this book. I'm particularly interested because my parents currently live in the Balkans (Albania), and my family was just weeks away from moving to Sarajevo in 1991 when the war broke out in Yugoslavia and we were relocated to Warsaw. I'm guessing this would be a valuable companion book to those who have read and enjoyed <i>Island of the World</i>.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8505808237850343490" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
